<FONT COLOR="#333399" face="Trebuchet MS, Arial, Helvetica">>>But for those it does bother, why not refrain from saying it to make their day more pleasant. <BR><BR>I suppose the same theory might be applied to those who crusade so vehemently to wipe the term dr00d from the face of EQ.  <BR><BR>*shrugs*  I'd rather prove to people that not all druids are bad than to type the many words it takes to argue about a term like dr00d in game.  Why cause more friction than there already is in EQ with a pointless argument?  I SoW, port, heal and otherwise help as I am able (time permitting).  I don't charge for these services, although I also believe that there is a way to request payment that is not abrasive.<BR><BR>For all my 58 levels I have spent 99.9% of my time visible to all.. (meaning NOT anon) Surprisingly enough I don't get beggar requests as much as you might think.. and my character name starts with an A so you can bet that I am on everyone's serverwide /w all druid.  I receive the occasional request for info on killing spots, spells and tactics from newbie druids.  I try to answer the questions as best I can or direct them to this site or CastersRealm.  I get requests for ports, too, and if I have the time and the request isn't outrageous, I try to accommodate.  If the request is an inconvenience, I have been practicing saying no as unoffensively as I can ever since I gained the ability to port.  (I do, however find it easier to refuse the few requests I get for rezzes, but that's a different story)<BR><BR>Rather than trying to move a mountain by arguing the PCness of the term dr00d, I prefer to help someone build the cart that can take him over the mountain with ease by demonstrating that not all druids are EBIL (now there is a word you can have some more fun with!)<BR><BR>But you're right.. different strokes for different folks.</FONT><BR></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR="#f7f5e6"><TD nowrap align="left">&nbsp;</TD><TD><table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspaci